Fire extinguished in French chemical plant
The major fire in a chemical plant in Rouen, France, considered to be particularly dangerous, was extinguished, and the prefecture of Normandy reported on Friday. The fire broke out at night on Thursday. No one was injured in the incident. The fire brigade was in operation with around 200 fire extinguishers.
The fire could be stopped
Buildings within a radius of 500 metres were evacuated, schools and kindergartens were closed on Thursday. Additives for lubricants are produced at the chemical plant on the banks of the Seine. The factory is part of the Lubrizol company of US billionaire Warren Buffett and is subject to the so-called Seveso Directive of the EU, which requires particularly strict safety requirements.
Around 400 people work at the plant. The chemical factory has already made headlines in the past - for example, when in 2013 the gas escaped methane thiol through a leak and the surrounding area smelled of rotten eggs. In 2015, about 2,000 litres of mineral oil flowed into the waste water system of the city after an industrial accident.
Woman quits her job to look for 57 days after her missing bitch
For two months a woman from Washington searched for her missing dog - and for that she quit her job. The seven-year-old Border Collie had escaped from the hotel room during a short vacation in Montana. 57 days was missing every trace of the bitch - but Carole King did not give up.
"It was terrible. I got sick," Carole King told "Daily Inter Lake." She and her husband had left Katie in the hotel room while they were going to dinner. When they returned to the hotel, Katie had disappeared. They were looking for the animal, but without success.
Thunder had panicked dog
In the hope that Katie could stay somewhere in the hotel, Carole King went to the front desk. "The employee says, "She left about four, four and a half hours ago," Carole King recalls to "Daily Inter Lake." When the automatic entrance door opened, Katie ran out immediately. Probably a loud thunder had panicked the dog.
With flyers and calls in Facebook groups, the Kings were looking for their beloved dog. But days have been weeks. "I have never given up. I have never lost hope," Carole King told the "Daily Inter Lake" who quit her job as a postal worker to continue her search for Katie.
"The tears flowed"
57 days after Katie's disappearance, Carole King got a phone call: A man called and said that Katie was in his yard. But when King arrived there, Katie had already disappeared again. She searched the neighborhood and suddenly her bitch stood under a tree. "I just hugged her. I didn't want to let her go," King remembered, according to "Daily Inter Lake." "The tears flowed. People stopped in their vehicles, got out and hugged us. I think the whole neighborhood knew we had found her."
Losses in the Bundeswehr: Machine guns disappear without a trace
Friday, September 27th, 2019
Six machine guns of the type MG3 have still disappeared.
In recent years, the Bundeswehr has lost numerous weapons and tens of thousands of rounds of ammunition, including three machine guns. In most cases, the whereabouts are unclear, and the opposition speaks of a "fearing" scale.
With the Bundeswehr, weapons and ammunition are disappearing again and again - many of them so far without a trace. Since the beginning of 2014, the force recorded the loss of 39 weapons, 39 parts of weapons and almost 20,000 rounds of ammunition. This is evident from a classified list of the Federal Ministry of Defense, which is reported by the editorial network Germany.
According to the paper from the office of Secretary of Defense Peter Tauber of the CDU, two weapons, one part of the gun and 3474 rounds of ammunition have reappeared so far. The still missing weapons and parts of the weapons include six machine guns of the type MG3, eleven guns of the type G3, four guns of the type G36, six signal guns as well as two pistols of the type P8. In addition, 30 gun pipes for machine guns of the type MG3 are missing.
The amount of gun and munitions losses in the Bundeswehr is "awesome," said left-wing member of the Bundestag Martina Renner. This is all the more true as little has been found in the course of investigations. The left-wing politician spoke of a "poor balance sheet". Renner criticized that the listing did not show whether the missing munitions were also the ones found in connection with the investigations against the suspected Bundeswehr officer Franco A.. "Even though a supporter of Franco A. was recently condemned for the possession of these munitions," said Renner.
