Mystery Solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. Scientists at Humboldt University in Berlin found out this with the help of experiments on rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. Progress was also made on the question why children resist tickling so violently, only to demand more.
Finally, it has also been shown why only the approaching of a tickling hand triggers laughter before the touch. This lies on a deep layer in the cerebrum, which triggers laughter already with the expectation of tickling.
According to the data, previous research showed that rats react with "Laughter" in the ultrasound range when tickled by humans. This "Laughter" is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex that serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughing is suppressed during self-touching
So far, it has been assumed that the brain can distinguish between self-contact and contact by others - that is, people cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers found out in the experiments on the rats that the laughter as well as the activity of the respective area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during a self-contact. This is also the case when living beings clean themselves. During the foreign contact and tickling by the scientists, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh have been intensified.
But if the self-contact and the contact by others at the same time, the laughter is also suppressed. This indicates that the brain of the rat cannot distinguish between the self-contact and the contact by others. The new findings suggest that people cannot tickle themselves because the self-contact activates a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. Thus, they sometimes broke off this initiation prematurely in the experiment, showed flight behaviour or fright. This ambivalence is similar to the behaviour of the children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioral reaction that is the same in rats and humans.
