Iran frees British tankers
The UN General Debate did not solve the Iran conflict, but now there is one less problem. The British oil tanker "Stena Impero" held in Iran was able to sink back into the sea. It could be a piece of the puzzle in the peace plan of Iranian President Ruhani.
The British oil tanker "Stena Impero", which has been detained in the Strait of Hormus in Iran since mid-July, is back in international waters. After being released by Iranian authorities, the ship is on its way to Dubai, according to the shipping company Stena Bulk.
The "Stena Impero" has left the port of Bandar Abbas and the crew is now going to Dubai for medical examinations, among other things, explained shipping company head Erik Hånell. At noon the ship left the Iranian waters. "It's nice that it's over," he told the Swedish TV channel SVT.
The Foreign Ministry in London described the ship as illegal. "This is part of a pattern of attempts to undermine the freedom of the seas. We are working with our international partners to maintain shipping and international law," said a statement on Friday.
The Iranian Revolutionary Guards had set the tanker on July 19 on the charge that they had disregarded the law of the sea in the Persian Gulf. Seven of the 23 crew members had already been released at the beginning of September. The remaining 16 crew members were doing well according to the circumstances, said Hånell. They had behaved professionally in view of the difficult and exhausting situation in the past ten weeks. The shipping company is now working to bring them back together with their families as soon as possible.
The British government suspected a reaction to a similar incident in Gibraltar at the beginning of July when a supertanker with oil from Iran, which is said to have been destined for Syria, was put on the chain. According to the authorities, the delivery violated EU sanctions against the war country Syria. The British had received the reference to the ship from the US.
Iran spoke of "piracy" and threatened with consequences. In mid-August, the "Adrian Darya-1" was finally released. London vehemently rejected the idea that it was a trade in order to free the "Stena Impero".
The Strait of Hormus is one of the most important seaways in the world. It connects the Persian Gulf with the Indian Ocean. Much of the world’s oil exports are shipped through the straits. Tensions in the region had increased immensely in recent months. Commercial shipping has been drawn into the conflict between the US and Iran. There have been several incidents with tankers and drones.
Behind the tensions between Tehran and Washington is the nuclear dispute between both countries. The Americans accuse the Iranian leadership of wanting to build nuclear weapons. Iran rejects this. The US had left the international nuclear agreement in 2018 alone, which should prevent Iran from building a nuclear bomb and at the same time end its political and economic isolation. Since then, the US government has put pressure on the leadership in Tehran with massive economic sanctions against the country in order to force a more stringent and extended agreement to other areas. Iran has resisted the pressure so far.
Because of the dispute over the "Stena Impero" and other incidents with tankers in the Persian Gulf and oil facilities in Saudi Arabia, the US is working on a coalition for military protection of merchant ships in the region.
Iranian President Hassan Ruhani presented a plan for security and peace in the Strait of Hormus at the UN General Assembly in New York. Iran, together with the Arab Gulf states and without foreign security forces, wants to ensure the safety of shipping in the Persian Gulf with the "Coalition of Hope" initiative for the Persian Gulf.
With its protectionist economic policy, India is building a better future.
India would actually be predestined to be a "war winner." Given the punitive tariffs imposed on Chinese producers by America’s President Donald Trump, foreign producers in the People’s Republic are forced to re-dispose. Financial leaders of Asian companies considering moving their production from China to another country call India one of the preferred alternatives in a UBS survey. Of course, this has not only to do with the uncertainties of the Chinese-American trade war. With a huge pool of young workers and a domestic market of 1.3 billion consumers, India seems to have created a more significant role to play in the world’s far-reaching production chain.
But now India itself has come to Trump’s attention. Derogating from the white house’s haudegen as the “kingdom of tariffs”, America deprived the emerging country of trade concessions for 2000 products at the beginning of June. The US accuses India of prohibitively high tariffs and calls for better market access for agricultural goods, mobile phones, spirits, motorcycles and more.
On the world map of trade wars, friction with India is, of course, just a side-show. America also looks at the world’s largest democracy through its security policy glasses. Delhi and Washington combine the concern about China’s claims to power in the South Indian Ocean. Against this background, a salvage of American punitive tariffs against India seems unlikely. India’s Prime Minister Narendra Modi, who has just entered a second five-year term, is therefore likely to weigh himself into safety.
However, the problem lies in a different place: The empirically substantiated thesis that open markets accelerate economic development has a difficult situation in the socialist Republic of India. Also under Modi. His zeal for reform is mainly aimed at the bureaucratic madness, which for too long suffocated any entrepreneurial spirit in the multi-ethnic state. Companies now receive faster building permits for buildings. They benefit from a better energy and transport infrastructure, and a more gripping insolvency and bankruptcy law creates conditions for liquidating companies with high debts more quickly.
The success of these efforts can be seen and measured in the relevant rankings. Much has changed for the better in India from an economic perspective in the first five years of Modi. However, this does not apply in trade policy. Inspired by this, the national conservative government even set new barriers to protecting internationally uncompetitive companies from foreign suppliers.
In the West, Modi is attached to the nimbus of the energetic reformer, who radically renews his country. This impression is not least due to the fact that the charismatic Prime Minister knows all too well what kind of vocabulary western managers like. In essence, however, the "India First" advocate never moved away from a protectionist economic policy, which prevents Indian companies from being forced to get rid of anachronistic processes and thus become fit for global competition. Businessmen who survive thanks to the foreclosure of their industries belong to the tribal voters of Modi's nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party and applaud this short-sighted policy.
