Bringing the competitor to the finish line: Dabo is the first secret hero of the World Championships in Athletics
The top of the world was already in the finish line long ago, when heartwarming scenes took place in the cooled Khalifa International Stadium. Jonathan Busby from Aruba began to wave dangerously in the first forerun of the men over 5000 meters. He could barely hold himself on his feet about 300 meters before the finish line, ran in an unhealthy way, when Braima Suncar Dabo from the West African country of Guinea-Bissau suddenly undercut him and supported him with the last half of the stadium round to the finish line. However, the forces were still sufficient for both of them to stop the watch running after the finish line. As if the scene had not already been curious enough.
"I just wanted to help him. Everyone in this situation would have done the same," said Dabo after the race in Mixed Zone, when he unexpectedly attracted the attention of the assembled journalists. Shy, he did not want to talk about his exploits at all. After all, he wanted to set up his personal best time and when he realized that this would be difficult, he only wanted to help a fellow sufferer. And anyway, he would only be proud to represent his country, which was invited for the World Cup by the World Federation. Under normal circumstances, he should not have even started. "That's why I'm proud to run here for my country," he said.
That’s what he did on the evening – and much more intensely than he would have thought. Because this feat will remain in memory. Especially as Dabo even left his competitor Busby ahead of the finish line and voluntarily took the last place - by the way, five minutes after the Ethiopian Selemon Barega, who won this preliminary run. In the end, it had done nothing, because the Busby, who only got to the finish line with much help, was disqualified at the end by the World Light Athletics Association.
Dabo, who lives in Portugal and studies there in Lisbon, had started to set a personal best time at the World Cup in Doha. According to official data, this succeeded with 18:10.87 minutes, but he himself was disappointed: "I wanted to run 17:55 minutes. I was already under 18 minutes." However, only in training, there are no best times.
Millionsmash: Egyptians Prepare for Wild Protest Day
In Egypt, security measures have been stepped up in the run-up to possible anti-government protests. An increased police presence was observed in the centre of Cairo on Friday. Several subway stations were closed, streets around central Tahrir Square were closed.
Already in recent days, the police had stepped up their road controls and partly searched the mobile phones of pedestrians on news and photos related to the protests. Hundreds had been arrested according to two non-governmental organisations.
Opponents of Al-Sisi
Last weekend, in Cairo, Alexandria, Suez and Mansura, there had been protests with hundreds of participants against the government of President Abdel Fattah al-Sisi, the critic of corruption and mismanagement. There had been no such open protest against the political leadership in Egypt for years. Egyptian builder and actor Mohammed Ali, who was living in exile in Spain, who started the demonstrations with video messages on Facebook, has called for a "millions march" in central places in the country for this Friday. Ali calls for a "people's revolution". The man is not "good" for most young Egyptians either, because he was a sub-contractor for the army, but his messages are coming.
The number of arrests related to the protests continued to increase according to two observer groups. The Egyptian Commission for Rights and Freedoms (ECRF) counted more than 1,570 arrests by Friday. The Egyptian Center for Economic and Social Rights (ECESR) and the human rights organization Human Rights Watch (HRW) spoke of more than 2,000 arrests. These figures could not be independently confirmed at first. The government also did not confirm or comment on the figures.
Arbitrary arrests
Many people were "arbitrarily arrested," "just because they were in the wrong place at the wrong time," HRW reported, referring to lawyers arrested. According to their lawyers, the allegations against the arrested range from "spreading false information" to membership in a "terrorist association." In Cairo, Alexandria and other cities, security forces questioned and searched in uniform, but also in civilian clothing, and according to HRW information, also random passersby.
HRW also criticized censorship in the North African country. According to this, the government in Cairo is blocking websites and online services to prevent further protests against Sisi.
Online Dealers: Mail order dealers should be able to donate returns more easily
For online retailers, many returned parcels are lost goods. Around 20 million returns end up in the garbage. But there is an alternative.
The Ministry of Finance has shown online retailers such as Amazon and Zalando a way to donate returned products instead of destroying them.
Although the companies could not be exempted from VAT on donations in kind, the Ministry explained to a question of the Greens-Bundestag group, which the newspapers of the Funke-Mediengruppe reported on Friday. However, traders could set the market value of the unsaleable returns so low that they had to pay no or only little VAT.
Scientists at the University of Bamberg had determined that the German citizens send back every sixth package of orders on the Internet. About four percent of the goods - about 20 million products - ended up in the garbage. According to current legal situation, to donate them would cost the companies additional money, because the financial authorities evaluate donations in kind like a turnover, which is then subject to VAT.
Green Group member Katrin Göring-Eckardt called on Finance Minister Olaf Scholz (SPD) to clarify with a decree that companies can evaluate non-sale products accordingly and donate them free of charge to non-profit organisations. Companies should be able to rely on not being punished for donations. This applies not only to online trade, but also to other shops from fashion shops to DIY stores.
