The well-known work of Streetart-Star Banksy, "Devolved Parliament", will soon be auctioned.
For Branczik, Banksys' work "emphasises the re-formation of the world's oldest parliamentary democracy into the basic attitude of animals and tribes." From Saturday, the painting will be exhibited at Sotheby's in the British capital until it is to be auctioned on 3 October. It is estimated at 1.5 to two million euros.
The work was first exhibited in the Bristol Museum in southwestern Britain in 2009, where Banksy lives. This year, the artist had exhibited the painting again, at the same time as the original Brexit date on 29 March. On this occasion, the work, formerly called "Question Time", was renamed "Devolved Parliament".
The picture could change ownership for a million dollars.
Most recently, Prime Minister Boris Johnson had made a hard trade with the opposition at the first meeting of the House of Commons following the suspension of a forced break by Johnson by the Supreme Court. Johnson wants to implement the Brexit, which had already been postponed twice on 31 October, even without any agreements with the EU if necessary.
This is not the first time Banksy, whose identity is still unknown, has intervened in the Brexit debate. In Dover, in south-eastern England, he painted a picture depicting a man who breaks a star of the European flag with a chisel. Thousands of truck drivers and other visitors see the factory every day when they enter the United Kingdom.
