Pakistan’s Prime Minister Khan Calls for Uno Intervention in Kashmir
With an emotional appeal, Pakistan's Prime Minister Imran Khan once again called on the United Nations to intervene in the Kashmir conflict at his first appearance at the UN General Assembly.
Otherwise, a renewed war between the nuclear powers Pakistan and India is likely, Khan said at the Uno General Debate in New York on Friday. "If that goes badly, one hopes for the best, but be prepared for the worst." The United Nations had a responsibility for Kashmir. "You should have prevented this."
India and Pakistan have waged three wars since their independence from British colonial rule in 1947, two of them around the divided region of Kashmir. Both nuclear powers dominate one part of Kashmir, another part belongs to China. At the beginning of August India had withdrawn autonomy status from the Indian Kashmir region and thus suddenly increased tensions in relation to Pakistan.
Not even a bottle of water
The demonstrators in Cairo demand the overthrow of the Egyptian President al-Sisi.
Against the current protests in Egypt, the government reacts with a hard hand. It shoots at the population with sharp ammunition, more than 2000 prisoners in the prisons join the 60,000 political prisoners who are already sitting there. Protesting has never been safe in Egypt. However, since the takeover of General Abdel Fattah el-Sisi in 2013, the state apparatus has been doing everything in its power to avoid a scenario like that of the Arab Spring.
But one of the triggers for the protests in 2011 was the poor economic situation. Poverty, lack of prospects and the feeling of being suffocated by one’s own government drove millions into the streets. And that’s a problem that el-Sisi’s regime can’t handle, no matter how hard it is against opponents. The situation has even worsened.
Today, every third person in Egypt lives below the poverty line. Since 2016, the currency has lost more than half of its value, the inflation rate is ten percent. If you want to buy a bottle of water in the supermarket, you have to decide who you are financing: Nestlé, Coca-Cola or the military. The latter is not only responsible for the suppression but also the biggest economic player. The military builds streets, houses, football stadiums, produces food and much more. That was already the case before el-Sisi. With authoritarian regimes, the Egyptian people have a lot of experience, even the dilemma in the supermarket is an old one.
Tüv tests in the terminal: BER boss: No more "showstoppers" for capital airport
Two months of testing was carried out to determine whether the complex plant mesh in the BER fire protection system works in conjunction. Operators are satisfied with the process. However, the Tüv is not yet finished at BER.
After large-scale Tüv inspections in the terminal of the future capital airport, the operators confirmed the planned opening in October next year. This is certain, said Chairman of the Supervisory Board Rainer Bretschneider after a meeting of the Supervisory Board.
Airport Chief Engelbert Lütke Daldrup spoke of a successful completion of the test, but also said that there are still shortcomings in the terminal. "We have many detailed topics, but we don't have a real showstopper." He assured that the timetable for commissioning still contains buffers.
However, there are indications that the time reserve should not be too large any more.The construction completion notice is now to be submitted to the construction office in the course of the first quarter of 2020, which was planned for this autumn at the beginning of the year.
Hundreds of defects in power cables still have to be repaired; the Tüv wants to check them by February. "In order to create the conditions here for the start of flight operations, there is still a need to work intensively on the processing of the defects," said a written communication.
Lütke Daldrup said that in many cases it is about missing evidence, less about new cables. There is also no release for all dowels on which the cable paths hang. The airport manager expects this to be available by the end of the year.
In addition, fire protection at the crossing to the station under the terminal is not yet working satisfactorily. The problems had led the project three years ago into another crisis. This time it is about smoke aprons, which run down in a fire like a screen, so that the smoke does not spread. They drive too far down. 36 engines must therefore be replaced. Then there will be new attempts with hot gas smoke at the beginning of the year.
Problems with fire protection and other construction defects as well as planning errors have delayed the opening of the airport for years. Originally it should go into operation in 2011. Since the start of construction in 2006, the costs have increased from two billion to approximately 6.5 billion euros for the opening next year.
Since the number of passengers in Berlin has increased significantly since then, the responsible parties are planning to expand the airport. This is why a special meeting of the Supervisory Board will take place on 18 October, as Chairman Bretschneider announced.
The airport company is now looking for two new managing directors. Head of finance Heike Fölster is moving to Deutsche Bahn at the end of the year, HR manager Manfred Bobke-von Camen retires next year, as Bretschneider said. He thanked Fölster. She had put the airport finances on firm feet.
Chemnitz: Automats for drugs blown up - police arrest man
He needed money for drugs - and blew up a lot of vending machines in the Chemnitz city area! Now the perpetrator is finally in jail!
Over the past two years, the number of blown-up cigarette and parking ticket machines in Chemnitz and the region has risen sharply.
After two detonations at the end of May, the police caught a 33-year-old German on Bürgerstraße and Further Straße in Chemnitz.
Police spokesman Andrzej Rydzik: "In the course of the investigation into the introduction of explosive explosions into the crime unit with a particularly serious case of the theft, which was led by the Chemnitz criminal police, not only this suspicion against the 33-year-old was confirmed."
Faced with the new evidence, the 33-year-old Chemnitzer now confessed a total of eight acts.
