US budget dispute: once again just a bridge financing
The new financial year will begin in the United States on 1 October without a proper budget. The Senate followed the House of Representatives on Thursday and decided on transitional financing until 21 November.
Although the US Congress and President Donald Trump agreed in August on an increase in expenditure ceilings for the financial years 2020 and 2021, the United States is once again without spending plans before the new fiscal year beginning on October 1st. The Senate followed the House of Representatives on Thursday and decided on a transitional financing (Continuing Resolution, CR) until November 21st. Without such a decision, a shutdown would have occurred on Monday at midnight, a partial closure of the federal administration. President Trump still has to put the decision into effect.
Shutdown averted
