After two earthquakes shook Western Turkey in a very short time, the fear of a disaster is growing. 34 people were injured in the earthquake on Tuesday. Since the quake the previous day, there have been almost 200 aftershocks, Turkish Vice President Fuat Oktay said on Friday. As a result, the fear of a disaster is growing.
14 schools in Istanbul were closed for security reasons. Hundreds of buildings were damaged. The earthquake of magnitude 5.8 on Thursday shook the Marmara region off Istanbul and caused panic in the metropolis of millions. Now the government wants to set up a commission to better prepare the country for earthquakes in the future, Oktay announced.
Over the past 20 years, Turkey has not been sufficiently prepared for quakes, said Istanbul’s mayor Ekrem Imamoglu. In the city itself, the latent danger is repeatedly ignored. Every year, poorly built housing collapses – among other things, the many smaller earthquakes that regularly shake Istanbul.
Urban planners such as the well-known architect Mücella Yapici have been warning for years that large open spaces that have been registered as shelters in the centre have long been built up. Only on the 20th anniversary of the Gölcük earthquake in August had the Istanbul Civil Engineering Chamber warned that an estimated one million buildings in Istanbul are not earthquake-proof.
The epicenter of the earthquake on Thursday was in the Marmara Sea in front of the district of Silivri and at a depth of about seven kilometres, as reported by the civil protection authority Afad. A minor aftershock caused even greater panic on the streets a few minutes later.
Istanbul’s mayor Ekrem Imamoglu said on Twitter that no casualties or damage had been reported at first. TRT, the state station, showed people running out of their homes in panic. Pupils were taken out of the buildings for security reasons in the Silivri district. Some students were crying, as can be seen in pictures.
Istanbul is considered to be particularly at risk of earthquakes. Under the Marmara Sea lies a section of the so-called North Anatolian disturbance, which marks the border between the Eurasian and Anatolian earth plates. Turkey is constantly shaken by earthquakes. One of the most deadly quake was in 1999 near Istanbul. At that time more than 17,000 people were killed.
Researchers fear that an earthquake of magnitude 7.1 to 7.4 could threaten. However, it is unclear when the earthquake will occur. During the earthquake on Thursday it hit again the west of the country and Istanbul.
Companies design emergency plans, private people have so-called go-bags packed with everything they need to stand next to front doors, and schools teach children how to behave when the earth shakes. When the next big quake comes is unclear.
Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan said after his return from New York that eight people had been injured and that some buildings had suffered minor damage. Istanbul Mayor Ekrem Imamoglu followed the developments of the Istanbul Disaster Coordination Centre (Akom), according to which two minarets of mosques collapsed in the districts of Avcilar and Sariyer.
