According to official data, the time of the quake is 1:59 p.m. (local time). According to CNN Turkey, only a few minutes after the first quake, there was an aftershock with a magnitude of 4.0 on the Richter scale.
Only on Tuesday an earthquake of magnitude 4.6 shook the Turkish Marmara region - it could be felt until Istanbul. Also its epicenter was located in the Marmara Sea west of the million metropolis, the civil protection authority Afad informed already on Tuesday.
It was not the only earthquake that made headlines this Tuesday: Pakistan was also hit by a severe earthquake.
Researchers assume that sooner or later there could be a catastrophic earthquake in Istanbul - the tension between the tectonic plates is extremely high. Scientists believe that it will eventually unload - and will cause massive damage.
Earthquake researcher Sükrü Ersoy reckons that the earthquake is now a warning. This has made it more likely, he said to CNN Türk. "These could be the signs of a major earthquake," Ersoy told the transmitter. "Early or later the great quake will also come."
