Half of the European tree species are threatened with extinction
In addition to pests, diseases, alien species, unsustainable logging and the growth of cities are also causes of the threat, reported the World Nature Conservation Union IUCN in Brussels on Friday. It examined the stocks of all 454 tree species known in Europe. 265 of these are not found on any other continent. 58 percent of these 265 are threatened. 66 are already at the highest level of danger and thus before extinction.
The IUCN divides endangered species into six categories: from "potentially endangered" to "at risk", "strongly endangered", "at risk of extinction" and "extinct in nature" to "extinct". In total, it lists more than 28,000 animal and plant species as endangered worldwide.
Scotch and wild horse chestnut threatened
In Germany, Ebereschen (Sorbus) is particularly threatened, said one of the authors, David Allen, of the German Press Agency. "Most of them are threatened because the populations are small or because of the transformation or weakening of their habitats."
It also looks bad for the wild ordinary horse chestnuts. They have been regarded as "hazardous" since 2017, level two of the IUCN scale. The biggest threat, besides a fungus, is the Balkan miner moth. It spreads from south-eastern Europe over the whole continent since the 1980s and has hardly any natural enemies. IUCN estimates the number of wild horse chestnuts (Aesculus hippocastanum) in Europe on less than 10,000 specimens. Not taken into account in this assessment are the trees in cities, parks and avenues.
Shrubs and mosses also in danger
The IUCN scientists also produced new European red lists for molluscs, shrubs and mosses. More than a fifth of molluscs and mosses and almost half of all shrub species are threatened, according to IUCN. This is mainly due to the destruction of the wilderness, introduced species, agricultural practices and climate change. Molluscs such as snails played a key role in the recycling of nutrients in the soil and are an important source of food for birds and other animals.
"This report shows that the situation is precarious for many overlooked and underestimated species, species that form the backbone of the European ecosystem and contribute to a healthy planet," said Luc Bas, IUCN Director of the European Office. "We must limit the impact of humans on our ecosystems and make the protection of these species a priority".
