With Linda McCartney, who had studied art history at the University of Aizona, until she found photography, the camera was always there. Thousands of Polaroids made it, a few hundred of them are now published for the first time in "The Polaroid Diaries".
They are portraits, still lifes, landscapes, several hamsters, a sheep in the kitchen and other interiors from the early 70s to the late 90s. "She wanted real moments," writes the art critic Ekow Eshun in his foreword. And of course there is always one in the center: her husband Paul - as you may have never seen him before.
There he dances with his daughter Mary on his shoulders, telephones in a bathrobe with a bag on his head or wears unshaped moonboats. Sure, the McCartneys were an extraordinary family, but beyond the spotlight on their farm in southern England or in Scotland also led a very normal life. Thus, according to the BBC, Mary McCartney said that she had slept as a baby in a bed that her father had made from old potato boxes. And also it has not always been tidyed up with the McCartneys.
Like hardly any other medium, the Poloraid camera captures the immediate moment. Linda McCartney’s recordings are certainly a kind of family diary, but they are much more than just snapshots.
It's about the decisive click: you have to recognize when a great photo happens before you. And then you have to snap it at the exact right moment," said Paul McCartney. "If you snap two seconds later or two seconds earlier, it can be a completely different photo." And Linda would have had the gift to always capture the exact right moment. "She just knew she had it," said Paul in the Eshun essay.
That's where the light, the composition, the cut-out and the colors are right, which makes "The Polaroid Diaries" not only an entertaining picture book for Beatles fans, but also a great aesthetic pleasure in addition to all the anecdotes, where landscapes also look like abstract paintings.The perfect complement to the newly released Beatles album "Abbey Road", which was released exactly 50 years ago.
