If the provider promises too much performance
If the Internet connection always seems to be much slower than advertised by the provider, there are different testing possibilities.
Anyone who enters into an internet contract does not need to blindly trust the speed information provided by the providers. Customers can themselves check how much of it is actually achieved in case of anomalies.
Finally, the previously promised transfer rates are a part of the contract and should therefore also be achieved, explains the Consumer Centre Bayern.
If the connection always seems to be much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various testing possibilities. For example, the measurement tools of the Federal Network Agency (BNetzA) measure the actual data transfer rates and compare them with the rate agreed in the contract.
"However, the tests of the providers are carried out according to provider-specific specifications and are therefore not uniformly and objectively calculated", says the Bayern Consumer Centre on its side.
If the connection is much slower than announced, customers can set the provider a reasonable period of usually 14 days to produce the promised performance. This is best done by writing a letter of formal notice.
If this does not affect anything even after several requests, customers can terminate their contract and may also demand damages. However, in the absence of success, only the legal remedy will help.
