Aegean: Baby and four more children drown in boat crash
A baby and four other children drowned while capping a refugee boat in the Aegean Sea. Seven people died in the accident, as the Greek Coast Guard reported on Friday. The nationalities are still unclear.
The boat sank near the Greek island of Inousses, which lies between the island of Chios and the Turkish mainland. Four children, three women and five men were saved.
Hundreds of migrants from Turkey are currently moving to the Greek islands in the east of the Aegean Sea. Last year, 174 people were killed on this route, according to the United Nations Refugee Agency (UNHCR). Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer has now announced his intention to visit both countries.
Together with his French colleague and the relevant EU Commissioner, he wanted to "inform Turkey about the refugee situation", said Seehofer on Friday. Afterwards, he wanted to learn more about the "administrative problems of the Greeks" in Athens, in order to be able to help deal with them.
On Friday, a spokesperson for the European Commission confirmed Seehofer's planned trip with EU Commissioner for the Interior Dimitris Avramopoulos and France's Interior Minister Christophe Castaner.
In Greece, an unusual number of migrants from Turkey continue to arrive. On Tuesday alone, 654 people transferred to the Greek islands, according to the Greek Ministry of Civil Protection on Wednesday.
Is the Turkey deal still working?
The increase in numbers has led to doubts about the functioning of the EU-Turkey Agreement concluded in 2016, which allows the EU to send back all refugees and migrants illegally coming to the Greek islands via Turkey. In return, the EU wanted to take in a Syrian refugee from Turkey for every deported Syrian.
However, the processing of asylum applications is difficult on the Greek side due to a lack of staff. According to the Ministry of Civil Protection, almost 29 400 people are waiting for Lesbos, Chios, Samos, Leros and Kos. The worst is the situation on Lesbos: 5200 migrats are currently housed in a camp with capacities for 650 people.
Never since the entry into force of the EU-Turkey Refugee Pact in March 2016 have there been so many, the state radio reported.
Climate change: Heat leads to more heart attacks
According to doctors, climate change will put the health system to the test in the future. Climate change is "very certain" one of the biggest challenges for the health system in the next 20 to 50 years, said Andreas Zeiher, President of the German Society of Cardiology. Especially the cardiovascular system caused high temperatures and large temperature jumps within a short time and led to increased heart attacks. Above all, people with cardiovascular diseases, elderly people and diabetics were affected.
Green politician has to answer for embarrassing photo breakdown
The leader of the Canadian Greens, Elizabeth May, in the election campaign, was the cup manipulated for this reason?
The Canadian green boss holds a reusable cup in her hand in a photo. But now it came out: The cup was manipulated.
Ottawa/Canada - It has remained unnoticed for quite a long time - and finally noticed. Elizabeth May, the head of the Canadian Green Party, never held the reusable coffee cup with metal straw in her hand. On the party's website she was on a photo with this cup, talking to citizens. However, the photo had already been published and also distributed to the media - and there the cup was still a nasty (Papp) cup, as the Canadian National Post reported.
Green boss has to answer for photo breakdown
The National Post then accused May of manipulation and that the Fake News party was producing in order to appear more credible on the subject of "environmental protection", in the middle of an election campaign for the House of Commons, in which Trudeau is also finding it increasingly difficult due to a bribery scandal.
The photo went viral in the social media and fanned the discussion about fake news. A user shares a juxtaposition of the photos and writes: "The Greens manipulate a photo of their presidents to hide their disposable cup".
May was shocked and affirmed on her blog that she did not know about this action. To underline this, she immediately posted the original: She, in conversation with citizens, a cup in her hand. However, she put it correctly, is made of bamboo. She always had it with her. A spokesperson of the party said that it was only about placing the party logo in the picture, not about covering up something. From the photo on the website only a section can be seen.
May writes that she is sorry for the employee who did this. "I don't want to call him stupid, but there was nothing to hide," she says to the Guardian and at the same time asked her over-engaged team: "If they want to work on a picture again, couldn't they do something with my face so I look younger?"
The German Greens have also come to Shitstorms because of their use of one-way plastic or because of air travels - but their pictures were not photoshopped. So the head of the Bavarian Greens, Katharina Schulze, ate ice cream with plastic spoons on holiday, as merkur.de* reported.
Influencer wants free upgrade: life-long flight ban at Cathay
Jaqueline Ng is said to have been promised an upgrade by mail from Cathay Pacific. But when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed on board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Spontaneously get an upgrade for the Business Class - many passengers dream of it. Sometimes they are lucky, and the staff at check-in offer a change from Economy Class free of charge.
This case shows, however, how not to do it: A self-declared influencer has actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. On Instagram follow Jaqueline Ng more than 65,000 users. On May 30th she flew back from Taiwan to New York and on June 7th.
On the way out, Jaqueline refused to upgrade, even though she presented an e-mail in which Cathay Pacific allegedly offered her an upgrade. The letter said that the influencer had received it from an airline marketing staff member, while the airline accused Jaqueline of falsifying the e-mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman presented the same mail, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK airport were sceptical: they were following up at the headquarters. And in fact, the employee from whom the mail allegedly came is said to have denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. This was also confirmed by the mail system in which the messages did not appear.
The airline staff at the airport cancelled Jaquelines Ticket and imposed a life-long flight ban with Cathay Pacific. For $1,400 (about €1,280) she had to buy a new flight tick to Taiwan.
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company representing consumer interests, because Cathay had refunded her the price of her original ticket, but Jaqueline also claimed the cost of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: For Cathay, the influencer has committed fraud, it remains blocked for future flights. The airline’s terms and conditions also state that she does not have to pay for the new flight. Jaqueline does not want to be satisfied with this - and now turns on a lawyer.
Oil prices give way according to report on armistice in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than one dollar in the shortest possible time on Friday afternoon. Most recently, a barrel (159 liters) of the North Sea variety Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - about 1.4 percent less than the previous day. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to 55.77 dollars.
The trigger for the course slide was a report by the Wall Street Journal on a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone attack on Saudi Arabia’s oil facilities had brought five percent of global oil production to a halt in mid-September. The Huthi rebels allied with Iran in the civil war country Yemen had claimed the attacks for themselves. Saudi Arabia, like the US government, blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse the political tension in the region.
If an agreement is actually reached, one can focus on growth and demand concerns, said Ole Hansen, Head of the Raw Materials Strategy Department at the Saxo Bank of Bloomberg news agency.
Oil prices are thus continuing their downward trend over the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had cost up to almost $59, Brent nearly $65.
Most recently, Bloomberg, relying on insiders, had reported that repair work on oil plants in Saudi Arabia progressed faster than expected after the attack in mid-September. According to this, the production volume had reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and moved again towards the original quantity.
Recently, there have been several press releases referring to insiders reporting on rapid progress made by the state oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. However, resource experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was some relief in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: the British oil tanker "Stena Impero" is on its way to leaving the port more than two months after Iran's arrest and the recently issued release.The crew now prepared the departure while the ship is still at anchor, shipping director Erik Hånell told the Swedish radio on Friday morning in a text message.
However, the US announced that it would transfer defense missiles and soldiers to the Iranian arch-enemy in Saudi Arabia. Fear of escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the US and Great Britain had pushed oil prices up sharply in recent weeks.
