North Korea deems Trump and Kim’s third summit to be questionable
North Korea has expressed doubts that in the nuclear dispute there will soon be a third summit of leaders Kim Jong-un and US President Donald Trump. Kim Kye-gwan, senior diplomat, said Friday, according to the agency KCNA, the purpose and prospects of such a meeting are questionable because of the lack of progress in implementing agreements reached at the first summit in Singapore.
The US had not done anything to implement the summit's decisions last year, said the adviser to the North Korean Foreign Ministry. He also criticised the US sanctions and the joint military manoeuvres of the US and South Korea. However, he hoped for Trump's "wise" and "courageous" decision to bring it closer again.
Trump had said on Monday that he wanted to know what a third summit meeting with Kim was to bring about before he agreed to do so. Negotiations on disarmament of the North Korean nuclear and missile programme have stalled since the failed second summit between Trump and Kim in Hanoi in February. In June, both met in the demilitarized zone between the two Korean states. In doing so, they agreed to revive the discussions, but so far without great success.
Prince Harry: Weapon manufacturers to help with mine clearance
In Angola, British Prince Harry symbolically detonated and destroyed an explosive mine. Near a camp of the British Halo Trust near Dirico, he produced the ignition circuit. At a safe distance, the explosive device exploded. Looking at the goal of getting Angola free of mines by 2025, he later demanded in front of running TV cameras: "I call on all the countries whose names stand on these weapons, but who have not helped to clear the way to commit themselves to help".
Pounds under pressure - interest rate reduction expected
British pound under pressure
In the face of an early interest rate cut, the pound is losing its value against the euro.
Frankfurt’s speculation that the Bank of England (BoE) would cut interest rates soon increases the pound sterling, and the British currency on Friday was reduced by up to 0.4 percent to 1.2269 dollars.
Sales were triggered by statements by central banker Michael Saunders, who talked about a reduction in interest rates, even if a chaotic Brexit could be averted, as uncertainty will affect the British economy for the foreseeable future. This statement is surprising, as Saunders is regarded as a defender of a restrictive monetary policy, said analyst Ricardo Evangelista of the broker house ActivTrades.
Last week, the Bank of England had already pointed out the burdens on the economy caused by the Brexit hack without directly signaling a rate cut. Prime Minister Boris Johnson wants to lead his country out of the EU on 31 October, if necessary, even without a divorce agreement.
